,{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[apxml](https://apxml.com/courses/introduction-to-neural-networks/chapter-3-forward-propagation/applying-activations)"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Key insight"},{"type":"text","text":": This two-step process ("},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"linear combination → activation"},{"type":"text","text":") defines computation within "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"each layer"},{"type":"text","text":" and repeats sequentially for all layers until the output."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Why Non-Linearity Enables Complex Learning"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"What non-linearity allows the network to do:"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"<table><tbody><tr><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">Complex decision boundaries</td><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">Learn curves, circles, and non-linear shapes (not just straight lines)</td></tr><tr><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">Hierarchical feature learning</td><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">Layer 1: simple edges → Layer 2: shapes → Layer 3: complex objects</td></tr><tr><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">Non-linear patterns</td><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">Capture complex interactions like XOR, not just linear relationships</td></tr><tr><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">Deep representation</td><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">Each layer learns a different level of abstraction</td></tr></tbody></table>"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Without activation functions, the network collapses to a single linear transformation regardless of how many layers you stack."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Practical Example: Complete Forward Pass with Activations"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Problem: 2-layer neural network for binary classification"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Input"},{"type":"text","text":": "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"X = [2.0, 1.5, 3.0]"}}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Layer 1 (Hidden layer with ReLU):"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Weights: "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"W^{} = \\begin{bmatrix} 0.5 & -0.3 & 0.8 \\\\ 0.2 & 0.4 & -0.1 \\end{bmatrix}"}}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Bias: "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"b^{} = [0.2, -0.1]"}}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Step 1: Linear Combination"}]},{"type":"blockMath","attrs":{"latex":"Z^{ [apxml](https://apxml.com/courses/introduction-to-neural-networks/chapter-3-forward-propagation/applying-activations)} = W^{ [apxml](https://apxml.com/courses/introduction-to-neural-networks/chapter-3-forward-propagation/applying-activations)} X + b^{ [apxml](https://apxml.com/courses/introduction-to-neural-networks/chapter-3-forward-propagation/applying-activations)} = \\begin{bmatrix} 3.15 \\\\ 1.0 \\end{bmatrix}"}},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Step 2: Apply ReLU Activation"}]},{"type":"blockMath","attrs":{"latex":"A^{ [apxml](https://apxml.com/courses/introduction-to-neural-networks/chapter-3-forward-propagation/applying-activations)} = \\operatorname{ReLU}(Z^{ [apxml](https://apxml.com/courses/introduction-to-neural-networks/chapter-3-forward-propagation/applying-activations)}) = \\begin{bmatrix} \\max(0, 3.15) \\\\ \\max(0, 1.0) \\end{bmatrix} = \\begin{bmatrix} 3.15 \\\\ 1.0 \\end{bmatrix}"}},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Both values are positive, so ReLU doesn't change them."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Layer 2 (Output layer with Sigmoid for binary classification):"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Weights: "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"W^{} = [0.6, -0.2]"}}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Bias: "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"b^{} = [0.3]"}}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Step 1: Linear Combination"}]},{"type":"blockMath","attrs":{"latex":"Z^{ [youtube](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LIKdvMhF_Yc)} = W^{ [youtube](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LIKdvMhF_Yc)} A^{ [apxml](https://apxml.com/courses/introduction-to-neural-networks/chapter-3-forward-propagation/applying-activations)} + b^{ [youtube](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LIKdvMhF_Yc)} = (0.6 \\times 3.15) + (-0.2 \\times 1.0) + 0.3 = 1.68"}},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Step 2: Apply Sigmoid Activation"}]},{"type":"blockMath","attrs":{"latex":"A^{ [youtube](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LIKdvMhF_Yc)} = \\operatorname{sigmoid}(1.68) = \\frac{1}{1 + e^{-1.68}} \\approx 0.84"}},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Final output"},{"type":"text","text":": 0.84 (interpreted as 84% probability of class 1)."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Applying Activations in Generative AI Models"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"How different Generative AI models use activations:"}]},{"type":"table","content":[{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan"